description: SLE is a chronic autoimmune disease characterized by a variety of symptoms, including rash, fever, joint pain and swelling, fatigue and anemia. In some cases, it can also lead to kidney damage and seizures.
treatment: Treatment for SLE typically involves medications to suppress the immune system, such as steroids and immunosuppressant drugs.

description: APS is an autoimmune disorder characterized by the presence of antibodies that attack proteins involved in the bodys natural blood clot prevention system. This can lead to a variety of symptoms, including blood clots, stroke, heart attack, and miscarriage. It can also cause kidney damage and neurological problems, such as seizure.
frequency: 50 per million each year in the US
severity: Moderate to high, depending on the specific symptoms
treatment: Treatment for APS typically involves long-term use of blood thinners to prevent clots, and possibly corticosteroids or immunosuppressive drugs to control the immune system.

description: HUS is a rare, serious condition characterized by the destruction of red blood cells, kidney failure, and low platelet counts. It can be caused by an infection or by taking certain medications. HUS can cause a variety of symptoms, including fever, seizures, bloody diarrhea, and bruising. Kidney damage can be severe and can lead to permanent kidney failure.
frequency: 2-3 per 100,000 children under age 5 each year in the developed world

treatment: Treatment for HUS typically involves supportive care, such as dialysis for kidney failure and transfusions of blood and platelets. In some cases, plasma exchange or immunosuppressive therapy may be used to help control the disease.

frequency: Unknown, but estimated to affect fewer than 1 in 100,000 people
severity: Varies depending on individual cases
treatment: There is no cure, but treatment may involve medications to suppress the immune system and dialysis or other treatments for kidney failure.

frequency: The rarest type of glomerular disease, about 1-2 cases per million people each year
severity: Severity depends on the type and underlying cause of MPGN

description: Infection in a joint, often caused by bacteria or other pathogens entering through the bloodstream or from a nearby infection. frequency: Affects about 2-4 per 100,000 people annually
severity: Can range from mild to life-threatening, depending on the severity of infection and underlying health
treatment: Antibiotics are the mainstay of treatment, but joint drainage or surgery might be needed in some cases.
